Observer: Not reported (details from summary email provided by Sabina Wilhelm July 15, 2022 "RE: Bird mortalities near Cape St. Mary's likely associated with HPAI")
Comments:
2022-07-13 email "Bird mortalities near Cape St. Mary's likely associated with HPAI" from Sabina says "Just a heads up that things appear to be unfolding rather quickly with respect to sick and dead birds on beaches on the Burin and St. Mary’s Bay, which points to Cape St. Mary’s birds. Just to get everyone on the same page: last Friday, reports were received of about 35 sick and dead primarily common murres and a few razorbills at Point May, Burin Peninsula. Todd Hollett, conservation officer based out of Winterland, picked up about a dozen (mostly murres, a few razorbills, two herring gulls and a black-backed gull) on Friday and has kept them frozen for pick up. Yesterday, Bill Montevecchi received reports of dead murres, gannets, and kittiwakes at Point La Haye. Today, Todd called me to say that he has been receiving many reports of additional dead birds but many live/sick, primarly murres and razorbills, at other beaches on the Burin and on the water near Taylor’s Bay and Lamaline. Shortly after receiving this phone call, Chris Mooney from Cape St. Mary’s contacted Chris Ward to say that he picked up today 15 common murres, 1 razorbill and 2 gannets (including a 4 year old) found dead near Branch. Note that this information was relayed to us while we were driving together back from Gull Island, after picking up a live razorbill found on a Ferryland beach showing neurological symptoms (this bird was dropped off at Animal Health this afternoon and was received by Meg Baker, along with an immature puffin and puffin chick found dead on Gull Island). In response to these reports, we are planning the following for tomorrow:
 - Chris Ward along with David Iles and Fiona Le Taro will be travelling to Cape St. Mary’s to pick up the birds collected by Chris Mooney for testing, conduct some beached bird surveys in the area, and if weather permits, deploy a zodiac to access Golden Bay, which is an excellent catchment beach for the area, as suggested by Chris M.
 - I will meet up with Todd Hollett in Goobies in the morning to collect the frozen birds picked up by Todd on Friday for testing and subsequently will head to Point La Haye to do a beached bird survey there."
